    <text>
        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                March 6&#44; 1890<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Dr.<lb/></p>
            <p>As the students have<lb/> received a day&#39;s vacation on<lb/> account of Purim&#44; I have not been<lb/> able to ask them concerning the<lb/> lectures delivered in the Semin&#45;<lb/>&#45;ary during the summer&#44; but<lb/> I will give them as far as<lb/> my memory services.  I do not<lb/> recollect the subjects of the<lb/> lectures during the first<lb/> summer term but the lectures<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>of the second term were<lb/> mainly as follows.  You<lb/> lectured on the characters<lb/> used in Hebrew writing and<lb/> on some biographical theme<lb/> from the Talmud.  Dr Mendes<lb/> spoke on &#34;The Taleth and the Toga&#34;<lb/> and &#34;the Taleth and the Pallium&#34;<lb/> being a comparison of Judaism<lb/> with Greek and Roman beliefs<lb/> and civilization.  Dr Adler spoke<lb/> on &#34;the relation of Assyriology to<lb/> the Bible&#34; and on &#34;the black obelisk<lb/> of Shalmaneser.&#34;  I spoke on<lb/> &#34;Jewish educational needs and<lb/> methods&#34; and on &#34;the kingdom<lb/> of Nusene.&#34;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>Names of Students and Attendants&#44;<lb/> Junior Department<lb/></p>
            <p>Regularly accepted students<lb/> Alexander Barovsky&#44; Henry Halpert&#44;<lb/> Joseph Hertz&#44; Sigmund Reich&#44;<lb/> Henry Speaker&#44; David Witten&#45;<lb/>&#45;berg.  Attendants all of whom<lb/> are applicants&#44; Gershon Feigen&#45;<lb/>&#45;bagum&#44; Friedman &#40;first name I<lb/> do not at this moment know&#41; Jacob<lb/> Sophie&#44; Joseph Weinberger.<lb/></p>
            <p>Preparatory Department<lb/> Regular Students<lb/> Benjamin&#44; Ehrenreich&#44; Samuel<lb/> Ehrenreich&#44; Michael Fried&#44;<lb/> W<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Friedman&#44; Max Goodman&#44;<lb/> Abraham D. Jacobs&#44; Maurice<lb/> Landon&#44; Charles Levy.<lb/></p>
            <p>Friedman was a regular scholar<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>who left for some time and has<lb/> now returned.<lb/></p>
            <p>Attendants<lb/></p>
            <p>Morris Mandel&#44; Moses Schreiber&#44;<lb/> Isaac Stoger.<lb/></p>
            <p>Mr Blumenthal gave me the letter of<lb/> Dr Cohen and I have sent him a<lb/> complete detailed statement of<lb/> everything as far as I could make<lb/> it out.<lb/></p>
            <p>I remain<lb/> very sincerely yours<lb/> Bernard Drachman<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
